    <div class="definition">
      <p>
      <h4 class="mt-5">Cálculo del Área de un triángulo con producto escalar</h4>       
      </p>
      <P> 
        Vamos a deducir una fórmula para el cálculo del área de un triángulo de lados \( \overrightarrow{A}  \)  y  \( \overrightarrow{B}  \) . <br>
        El vector altura es entonces:
        \[ \overrightarrow{h}=\overrightarrow{B}-\overrightarrow{PyccnB/A}=%
        \overrightarrow{B}-\dfrac{\left( \overrightarrow{B}\cdot \overrightarrow{A}%
        \right) }{\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}}\overrightarrow{A}  \]
        Si hacemos \( \alpha=\left( \overrightarrow{B}\cdot \overrightarrow{A}\right) \) y \( \beta=\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}  \)
        tenemos:
        \[ \overrightarrow{h}=\overrightarrow{B}-\overrightarrow{PyccnB/A}=%
        \overrightarrow{B}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta}\overrightarrow{A}  \]
        Ver Figura 7
      </P> 
      <p>  
        <figure>
          <img src="assets\images\VPE_Area_prodEscalar.svg" class="img-fluid mx-auto d-block" 
           alt="Responsive image" height="auto" >
          <figcaption class="figure-caption text-center">Figura 7</figcaption>
     </figure>
      </p>
      <p>
        Por la propiedad de norma del producto escalar tenemos que:
        \[  \left\Vert \overrightarrow{h}\right\Vert ^{2}=\left( \overrightarrow{B}-%
        \dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }\overrightarrow{A}\right) \cdot \left( 
        \overrightarrow{B}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }\overrightarrow{A}\right) \]
  
        \[   =\overrightarrow{B}\cdot \left( \overrightarrow{B}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }%
        \overrightarrow{A}\right) -\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }\overrightarrow{A}\cdot
        \left( \overrightarrow{B}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }\overrightarrow{A}\right) \]
  
        \[ =\left\Vert \overrightarrow{B}\right\Vert ^{2}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }%
        \overrightarrow{B}\cdot \overrightarrow{A}-\dfrac{\alpha }{\beta }%
        \overrightarrow{A}\cdot \overrightarrow{B}+\dfrac{\alpha ^{2}}{\beta ^{2}}%
        \left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}  \]
        
      </p>
      <p>Operando a fin de simplificar tenemos:
        \[  \left\Vert \overrightarrow{h}\right\Vert ^{2}=\dfrac{\beta ^{2}\left\Vert 
        \overrightarrow{B}\right\Vert ^{2}-\beta ^{2}\dfrac{2\alpha }{\beta }%
        \overrightarrow{A}\cdot \overrightarrow{B}+\alpha ^{2}\left\Vert 
        \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}}{\beta ^{2}} \]
  
        \[  =\dfrac{\beta ^{2}\left\Vert 
        \overrightarrow{B}\right\Vert ^{2}-\beta 2\alpha \overrightarrow{A}\cdot 
        \overrightarrow{B}+\alpha ^{2}\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}}{%
        \beta ^{2}} \]
       
  
        </p>
        <p> Devolviendo el cambio de los escalares \( \alpha \)  y  \( \beta \)
        \[  \left\Vert \overrightarrow{h}\right\Vert ^{2}=\dfrac{\left\Vert 
          \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{4}\left\Vert \overrightarrow{B}\right\Vert
          ^{2}-\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}2\left( \overrightarrow{B}%
          \cdot \overrightarrow{A}\right) \overrightarrow{A}\cdot \overrightarrow{B}%
          +\left( \overrightarrow{B}\cdot \overrightarrow{A}\right) ^{2}\left\Vert 
          \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}}{\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert
          ^{4}} \]
  
        \[ \left\Vert \overrightarrow{h}\right\Vert ^{2}=\dfrac{\left\Vert 
          \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{4}\left\Vert \overrightarrow{B}\right\Vert
          ^{2}-\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}\right\Vert ^{2}\left( \overrightarrow{B}%
          \cdot \overrightarrow{A}\right) ^{2}}{\left\Vert \overrightarrow{A}%
          \right\Vert ^{4}}  \]
  
